# Executive Summary
## The Gauss–PowerLaw Module (GPM): A New Early-Warning System for Financial Risk

**Author:** László Tatai / BarefootRealism Labs  
**Date:** April 2026  
**Contact:** ORCID 0009-0007-5153-6306

---

## The Problem

Every major financial crisis of the past two decades was preceded by the same
invisible structural change: the statistical distribution of market returns
quietly shifted from well-behaved (Gaussian) to extreme (heavy-tailed).
When this happens, standard risk models break down. Sharpe ratios become
meaningless. Value-at-Risk underestimates true exposure. The tools that
practitioners rely on silently lose their validity — before anyone notices.

The question is: **can this shift be detected before the crisis, not after?**

---

## The Answer

Yes. And it can be measured with a single number.

This work introduces **delta_GARCH** — a real-time indicator derived from
standard GARCH volatility estimation — that measures how close a market is
to the critical boundary where normal statistical inference collapses.

When **delta_GARCH crosses zero from above, the market has entered the
danger zone.** CLT-based inference is no longer valid. Heavy tails are
no longer a tail risk — they are the dominant regime.

---

## The Evidence

Validated on **seven real markets** using daily data from 2002 to 2026:

| Market | Crisis detected | Signal timing |
|--------|----------------|---------------|
| S&P 500 | Lehman 2008, 2018 volatility | Weeks before peak |
| NASDAQ | 2008, COVID 2020, 2022 | Consistent pre-crisis warning |
| DAX | 2008, 2020, 2022 | European confirmation |
| OTP Bank (Hungary) | 2008, 2015–16 | Emerging market profile |
| Mercedes-Benz | 2023–2026 | Currently in danger zone |
| Bitcoin / USD | Persistent | Chronically in extreme regime |
| USD / EUR | 2008 (brief) | Reference: stable baseline |

The signal is **not a forecast**. It is a structural diagnostic — like a
pressure gauge. When pressure exceeds the critical threshold, the system
has already changed. The question is no longer whether a crisis will come,
but how large it will be.

---

## The Theory (Non-Technical)

Standard GARCH models describe *how volatile* a market is.
The Gauss–PowerLaw Module (GPM) asks a deeper question:
*why do extreme events cluster the way they do?*

The answer is a **bifurcation** — a structural tipping point in the coupled
dynamics of volatility and tail behavior. Below the tipping point, the system
is Gaussian: standard statistics apply. Above it, the system has crossed into
power-law territory: standard statistics break down.

This paper proves — algebraically, not just empirically — that the tipping
point identified by López de Prado, Porcu, Zoonekynd & Engle (2026) in their
Sharpe ratio inference framework is **mathematically identical** to the GPM
bifurcation. Two independent derivations, one critical boundary.

> GARCH captures the symptom.  
> The GPM captures the mechanism.

---

## What This Means in Practice

**For risk managers:** delta_GARCH provides a real-time regime indicator.
When it turns negative, reduce exposure to models that assume normality.

**For quantitative researchers:** the GPM provides a mechanistic foundation
for heavy-tail emergence — not as an assumption to be estimated,
but as a structural consequence to be derived.

**For portfolio managers:** the Sharpe ratio loses its meaning when
delta_GARCH < 0. Alternative risk functionals (fractional Sharpe,
as proposed by López de Prado et al., 2026) should be applied instead.

**For regulators:** the indicator provides a market-wide structural
diagnostic that is independent of any specific model or institution.

---

## What Is Included in This Release

- **Full theoretical paper** with formal proofs (Lemma 1, Theorem 1,
  Theorem 2, completed Appendix)
- **Python implementation** — open source, reproducible, documented
- **Empirical results** — seven markets, timestamped figures and data
- **Integrity verification** — all documents available in MDL format
  (cryptographic authorship and timestamp proof)

---

## Key Result in One Line

$$\Delta_{\text{GPM}} = 0 \;\Longleftrightarrow\; \varphi_4 = 1
\;\Longleftrightarrow\; \kappa = 4
\;\Longleftrightarrow\; \mathbb{E}[y^4] = \infty$$

*Four equivalent conditions. One critical boundary.
Detectable in real time. Proven from first principles.*

